Feminism is important. Here are several more examples why we need feminism:

Blatant sexism permeates economic, social and economic life
Women want to be called strong, not bitchy
Women should never need to apologize for their success
Urgent need to accept people of all genders and identities
Women do not need to be told how to live their life
We need to get rid of hypocrisy and double standards when talking about women
We need to erase the gender binary
Men who are called feminists should not be mocked
One day, the word feminism will become obsolete.

img__alt: Photo by Oskar Ulysses on September 17, 2020.
initial_comment:
Every Mexican celebrated or posted something for the
Mexican Independence Day
Wed, Sep 16, 2020

Which was a pivotal moment in 1808 to 1821, resulting in Mexico's independence from Spain.

But I rarely see Mexican folks post this or even talk about it amongst our own people.
In 2020 women in Mexico are demanding action by their government for their safety and well being.

What we should be doing is Creating awareness and standing up for the Mexican women that are victims Of this femicide.
What is Femicide?
Femicide, also known as feminicide, is defined in a report by the World Health Organization (WHO) as "intentional murder of women because they are women." Similarly, it is defined by UN Women, UNiTe to End Violence Against Women

Since 2015 rates of femicide in Mexico have increased by 145% and as bad as this is going to sound this number is incomplete due to the fact that several states in Mexico do not count femicide as murder. This is unacceptable.

Almost 1000 women have been killed in 2020 which has led to the massive protest outside the Mexican palacio nacional.
Most femicide crimes are committed by partners or ex partners and involve ongoing abuse at home, threats of intimidation, sexual violence or situations where women are vulnerable. This has been a federal crime since 2012 which is shocking to me that it‚Äôs only been 8 years that this has been charged as a federal crime.

Women are being murdered in Mexico at an alarming rate, but the nation's president has downplayed a surge in calls to emergency hotlines, declaring most of them are false.
Victims themselves may be afraid to call for help if they live with the aggressor, or even to file claims. "If authorities arrive. If they arrive which we all know that they sometimes don‚Äôt due to the Low resources in government agencies available to the people.

This needs to change and I feel like we have the opportunity to help when we go to Mexico on vacation every year for the towns festivals by creating awareness which in Mexico is very rare since there are still a lot of the male machismo crap going around.
#femicidio #femicide #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #protectourfemales

‚ÄúMEXICO‚ÄôS
MISSING AND MURDERED
The numbers are staggering: Six women killed every day, according to one organization. Over the past two decades, reports Brooke Binkowski in Mexicali, Mexico, the killing or disappearance of women has become so frequent, a new term has entered the country‚Äôs lexicon: femicidio.‚Äù
#vday 
#mmiw #femicideinmexico #oursisters #daughters #mothers #tias #abuelitas #sisternation 

BROOKE BINKOWSKI
MEXICALI, MEXICO
SPECIAL TO THE GLOBE AND MAIL
PUBLISHED JULY 12, 2015
initial_comment:
25-year-old Ingrid Escamilla from Mexico City, Mexico was savagely murdered and skinned this past weekend.
Police officers arrived at the scene Sunday, to find Escamilla on the floor, lifeless with her body skinned and missing some organs. A 46-year-old man was also at the scene, covered in blood. Photos and videos have surfaced in which the man has admitted to stabbing the woman after a heated argument in which she threatened to kill him.
Further outrage sparked when digital news sites and local tabloids began posting extremely gruesome leaked photographs of the victim's body. One of the papers, Pasala, showed the photos on its front page alongside the headline "It was Cupid's fault." Prosecutors said they will demand the maximum sentence against the alleged perpetrator, whom police said was the woman's husband.
Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before.

#PulpMagazineüçä #FemicideinMexico

initial_comment:
Some of you may have heard and some of you may not have a clue about what happened to this woman.
.
.
This 25 years old woman was murdered. She was skinned to "hide the evidence." Graphic pictures of her were leaked and posted online. One news paper went as far as to plaster it on their front page with the caption, "it was Cupid's fault." She was murdered by her husband after a heated argument. .
.
This woman was only 25 years old. Her life was cut short. She is one of the many victims of Femicide in Mexico.
.
.
For those that don't know -- "Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before." .
.
"The United Nations has rated Mexico as one of the most violent countries for women in the world."
.
.
This type of violence needs to end! What happened to Ingrid is so inhumane, especially having pictures of her mutilated body be displayed on the front page of a news paper for the world to see.
.
.
Please, if you see any graphic pictures of her do not repost them. That's just so wrong.
#IngridEscamilla #Femicide #EndFemicide #FemicideInMexico #RestInPeaceIngrid

initial_comment:
FEMICIDE IN MEXICO
Femicide is a gender-normed violence that most of the time involves mental, physical, and emotional abuse. Femicide itself represented 10% of all murder in Mexico back in 2019, which is Mexico‚Äôs most violent year. There are multiple cases of women missing or found dead, however many of them aren‚Äôt investigated or reported. Sadly till this day, there are many victims who haven‚Äôt had the courage to seek help or report their cases. This is why we decided to address this on our Instagram account, @thehowlsproject, because we want to make more people aware of this topic. We might have missed some things, so feel free to talk about it in our comments below or our dms, and you could also share your opinion regarding the topic.

**BAHASA INDONESIA VERSION AVAILABLE AT OUR ACC**

FOR MORE INFORMATION:
https://femicidesmex.carrd.co/# (includes petition that you can sign)

https://www.csis.org/analysis/femicides-mexico-impunity-and-protests
https://www.statista.com/statistics/979076/mexico-number-femicides-month/
https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2021/03/09/womens-day-protests-amlo-mexico/
https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/26/desperation-and-rage-mexican-women-take-to-streets-to-protest-unabated-sexual-violence-glitter-revolution

Femicide is a gender-normed violence that most of the time involves mental, physical, and emotional abuse. Femicide itself represented 10% of all murder in Mexico back in 2019, which is Mexico‚Äôs most violent year. There are multiple cases of women missing or found dead, however many of them aren‚Äôt investigated or reported. Sadly till this day, there are many victims who haven‚Äôt had the courage to seek help or report their cases. This is why we decided to address this on our Instagram account, @thehowlsproject, because we want to make more people aware of this topic. We might have missed some things, so feel free to talk about it in our comments below or our dms, and you could also share your opinion regarding the topic.

**BAHASA INDONESIA VERSION AVAILABLE AT OUR ACC**

Before the just celebrated International Women‚Äôs Day, the government of Mexico erected a fence to protect Mexico's National Palace due to planned marches to mark the Day.
This was in turn turned into a memorial by women's rights activists who wrote the words, "Victims of Femicide" in huge letters and the names of thousands of victims on this 3m high barrier.
It was a way to draw attention to the hundreds of femicide victims killed every year in Mexico where reports show that the government is not doing enough to combat it.
‚ö†Ô∏èFigures suggest a staggering number of at least 939 victims of femicide was recorded in 2020 alone‚ö†Ô∏è

initial_comment:
Top headlineüö®

Swipe for more info‚û°Ô∏è

#mexico #femicide #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #breakingnews #topheadlines #southamerica #latinamerica #centralamerica #caribbean #information #advocacy #education #articles #writeforus #latinx

We must openly and widely recognize that the state mandates issued --allegedly as part of the "response to the pandemic"-- are having a direct impact on the rise of domestic violence and the murders of women around the world. 
Male violence is increasing and impunity is growing. 

The president of Mexico has repeatedly made dismissive comments claiming the all-time-high phone calls to domestic violence hotlines are what he referred to as "prank calls". 

A direct quote from President Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, ‚ÄúNinety per cent of those calls that you‚Äôre referring to are fake." 

1000 women were murdered in a 3 month period and 90 percent of the calls for help are fake? Think of all the women who are abused or being trafficked and don't even have access to a phone to attempt to make a call to a crisis line. I guarantee there are more women at risk than the increase in calls to the hotlines imply.

I find it interesting that the Mexican president has been hailed as Mexico's "first leftist president in decades". His inaugural message included a statement about "equality" for LGBT (which is a dog whistle..."equality" = inclusion of males in female spaces / erasure of female sex segregated spaces).

In articles I have read he has defended himself and his administrations failure to alleviate epidemic levels of violence against women by claiming that "conservatives are dressing up as feminists to attack him". 

The Mexican President has blamed conservative political groups for protests that brought tens of thousands of people into the streets to demand an intervention on male violence against women.  

In America we also have left-wing political pundits and "activists" that attempt to dismiss and brand women who speak out against female erasure under the guise of "trans rights" as, "conservatives", "nazis", "bigots", "transphobes", and "TERFS". 

[full comments begin on slide #3]
#nounamas #femicide #violenceagainstwomen #radfem #radicalfeminism #femicideinmexico #gendercritical #womensrights #femaleerasure #femalerights #vawa #whateverywomanneedstoknow #thedeprogrammer

initial_comment:
La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

initial_comment: #challengeaccepted Thank you @bruna.sizzi @saharaness _ @__hastifazli__ for inviting me to this challenge. At first I was hesitant to post a picture but I realize that there may hav been some misunderstandings regarding why women are posting pictures of themselves using this hashtag. The intention of this challenge is to raise awareness on the subject of hate and violence against women and more specifically #femicide in Turkey, Iran and the many other countries which some women are unfortunately born into or married in close minded and sexist families. In these cases, women are often perceived as an object and ‚Äúproperty‚Äù of the man(men) of the family. Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. Stay #strong I now challenge @bitamajidi_ #istanbulturkey #iran #femicideawareness #femicideinturkey #femicideinmexico #femicideiniran #strongwomen #womenempowerment #feminismmemes

initial_comment:
Every Mexican celebrated or posted something for the
Mexican Independence Day
Wed, Sep 16, 2020

Which was a pivotal moment in 1808 to 1821, resulting in Mexico's independence from Spain.

But I rarely see Mexican folks post this or even talk about it amongst our own people.
In 2020 women in Mexico are demanding action by their government for their safety and well being.

What we should be doing is Creating awareness and standing up for the Mexican women that are victims Of this femicide.
What is Femicide?
Femicide, also known as feminicide, is defined in a report by the World Health Organization (WHO) as "intentional murder of women because they are women." Similarly, it is defined by UN Women, UNiTe to End Violence Against Women

Since 2015 rates of femicide in Mexico have increased by 145% and as bad as this is going to sound this number is incomplete due to the fact that several states in Mexico do not count femicide as murder. This is unacceptable.

Almost 1000 women have been killed in 2020 which has led to the massive protest outside the Mexican palacio nacional.
Most femicide crimes are committed by partners or ex partners and involve ongoing abuse at home, threats of intimidation, sexual violence or situations where women are vulnerable. This has been a federal crime since 2012 which is shocking to me that it‚Äôs only been 8 years that this has been charged as a federal crime.

Women are being murdered in Mexico at an alarming rate, but the nation's president has downplayed a surge in calls to emergency hotlines, declaring most of them are false.
Victims themselves may be afraid to call for help if they live with the aggressor, or even to file claims. "If authorities arrive. If they arrive which we all know that they sometimes don‚Äôt due to the Low resources in government agencies available to the people.

This needs to change and I feel like we have the opportunity to help when we go to Mexico on vacation every year for the towns festivals by creating awareness which in Mexico is very rare since there are still a lot of the male machismo crap going around.
#femicidio #femicide #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #protectourfemales

In 2020 women in Mexico are demanding action by their government for their safety and well being.

What we should be doing is Creating awareness and standing up for the Mexican women that are victims Of this femicide.
What is Femicide?
Femicide, also known as feminicide, is defined in a report by the World Health Organization (WHO) as "intentional murder of women because they are women." Similarly, it is defined by UN Women, UNiTe to End Violence Against Women

Since 2015 rates of femicide in Mexico have increased by 145% and as bad as this is going to sound this number is incomplete due to the fact that several states in Mexico do not count femicide as murder. This is unacceptable.

Almost 1000 women have been killed in 2020 which has led to the massive protest outside the Mexican palacio nacional.
Most femicide crimes are committed by partners or ex partners and involve ongoing abuse at home, threats of intimidation, sexual violence or situations where women are vulnerable. This has been a federal crime since 2012 which is shocking to me that it‚Äôs only been 8 years that this has been charged as a federal crime.

Women are being murdered in Mexico at an alarming rate, but the nation's president has downplayed a surge in calls to emergency hotlines, declaring most of them are false.
Victims themselves may be afraid to call for help if they live with the aggressor, or even to file claims. "If authorities arrive. If they arrive which we all know that they sometimes don‚Äôt due to the Low resources in government agencies available to the people.

This needs to change and I feel like we have the opportunity to help when we go to Mexico on vacation every year for the towns festivals by creating awareness which in Mexico is very rare since there are still a lot of the male machismo crap going around.
#femicidio #femicide #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #protectourfemales

The numbers are staggering: Six women killed every day, according to one organization. Over the past two decades, reports Brooke Binkowski in Mexicali, Mexico, the killing or disappearance of women has become so frequent, a new term has entered the country‚Äôs lexicon: femicidio.‚Äù

SPECIAL TO THE GLOBE AND MAIL
PUBLISHED JULY 12, 2015
initial_comment:
25-year-old Ingrid Escamilla from Mexico City, Mexico was savagely murdered and skinned this past weekend.
Police officers arrived at the scene Sunday, to find Escamilla on the floor, lifeless with her body skinned and missing some organs. A 46-year-old man was also at the scene, covered in blood. Photos and videos have surfaced in which the man has admitted to stabbing the woman after a heated argument in which she threatened to kill him.
Further outrage sparked when digital news sites and local tabloids began posting extremely gruesome leaked photographs of the victim's body. One of the papers, Pasala, showed the photos on its front page alongside the headline "It was Cupid's fault." Prosecutors said they will demand the maximum sentence against the alleged perpetrator, whom police said was the woman's husband.
Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before.

initial_comment:
Some of you may have heard and some of you may not have a clue about what happened to this woman.
.
.
This 25 years old woman was murdered. She was skinned to "hide the evidence." Graphic pictures of her were leaked and posted online. One news paper went as far as to plaster it on their front page with the caption, "it was Cupid's fault." She was murdered by her husband after a heated argument. .
.
This woman was only 25 years old. Her life was cut short. She is one of the many victims of Femicide in Mexico.
.
.
For those that don't know -- "Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before." .
.
"The United Nations has rated Mexico as one of the most violent countries for women in the world."
.
.
This type of violence needs to end! What happened to Ingrid is so inhumane, especially having pictures of her mutilated body be displayed on the front page of a news paper for the world to see.
.
.
Please, if you see any graphic pictures of her do not repost them. That's just so wrong.
#IngridEscamilla #Femicide #EndFemicide #FemicideInMexico #RestInPeaceIngrid

FEMICIDE IN MEXICO
Femicide is a gender-normed violence that most of the time involves mental, physical, and emotional abuse. Femicide itself represented 10% of all murder in Mexico back in 2019, which is Mexico‚Äôs most violent year. There are multiple cases of women missing or found dead, however many of them aren‚Äôt investigated or reported. Sadly till this day, there are many victims who haven‚Äôt had the courage to seek help or report their cases. This is why we decided to address this on our Instagram account, @thehowlsproject, because we want to make more people aware of this topic. We might have missed some things, so feel free to talk about it in our comments below or our dms, and you could also share your opinion regarding the topic.

**BAHASA INDONESIA VERSION AVAILABLE AT OUR ACC**

FOR MORE INFORMATION:

FEMICIDE IN MEXICO
Femicide is a gender-normed violence that most of the time involves mental, physical, and emotional abuse. Femicide itself represented 10% of all murder in Mexico back in 2019, which is Mexico‚Äôs most violent year. There are multiple cases of women missing or found dead, however many of them aren‚Äôt investigated or reported. Sadly till this day, there are many victims who haven‚Äôt had the courage to seek help or report their cases. This is why we decided to address this on our Instagram account, @thehowlsproject, because we want to make more people aware of this topic. We might have missed some things, so feel free to talk about it in our comments below or our dms, and you could also share your opinion regarding the topic.

Before the just celebrated International Women‚Äôs Day, the government of Mexico erected a fence to protect Mexico's National Palace due to planned marches to mark the Day.
This was in turn turned into a memorial by women's rights activists who wrote the words, "Victims of Femicide" in huge letters and the names of thousands of victims on this 3m high barrier.
It was a way to draw attention to the hundreds of femicide victims killed every year in Mexico where reports show that the government is not doing enough to combat it.
‚ö†Ô∏èFigures suggest a staggering number of at least 939 victims of femicide was recorded in 2020 alone‚ö†Ô∏è

initial_comment: For this week‚Äôs feminist friday we‚Äôll be looking at the ongoing scourge of femicide that is occurring within Mexico. Many women in Mexico are calling for action against Mexico‚Äôs corrupt justice system. The system has failed thousands of women who were killed and 98% of cases go unprosecuted. Cases are rising and many women feel unsafe and fear for their lives. There needs to be change and policies that help protect women, this is not just a feminist issue but a human rights issue as everyone has the right to not live in fear of being killed/murdered. #mejorvivasquecatrinas #femicide #nojusticia #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #thethreedeathsofmariselaescobedo

initial_comment:
La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

initial_comment: #challengeaccepted Thank you @bruna.sizzi @saharaness _ @__hastifazli__ for inviting me to this challenge. At first I was hesitant to post a picture but I realize that there may hav been some misunderstandings regarding why women are posting pictures of themselves using this hashtag. The intention of this challenge is to raise awareness on the subject of hate and violence against women and more specifically #femicide in Turkey, Iran and the many other countries which some women are unfortunately born into or married in close minded and sexist families. In these cases, women are often perceived as an object and ‚Äúproperty‚Äù of the man(men) of the family. Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. Stay #strong I now challenge @bitamajidi_ #istanbulturkey #iran #femicideawareness #femicideinturkey #femicideinmexico #femicideiniran #strongwomen #womenempowerment #feminismmemes

img__alt: Photo by Oskar Ulysses on September 17, 2020.
initial_comment:
Every Mexican celebrated or posted something for the
Mexican Independence Day
Wed, Sep 16, 2020

Which was a pivotal moment in 1808 to 1821, resulting in Mexico's independence from Spain.

But I rarely see Mexican folks post this or even talk about it amongst our own people.
In 2020 women in Mexico are demanding action by their government for their safety and well being.

What we should be doing is Creating awareness and standing up for the Mexican women that are victims Of this femicide.
What is Femicide?
Femicide, also known as feminicide, is defined in a report by the World Health Organization (WHO) as "intentional murder of women because they are women." Similarly, it is defined by UN Women, UNiTe to End Violence Against Women

Since 2015 rates of femicide in Mexico have increased by 145% and as bad as this is going to sound this number is incomplete due to the fact that several states in Mexico do not count femicide as murder. This is unacceptable.

Almost 1000 women have been killed in 2020 which has led to the massive protest outside the Mexican palacio nacional.
Most femicide crimes are committed by partners or ex partners and involve ongoing abuse at home, threats of intimidation, sexual violence or situations where women are vulnerable. This has been a federal crime since 2012 which is shocking to me that it‚Äôs only been 8 years that this has been charged as a federal crime.

Women are being murdered in Mexico at an alarming rate, but the nation's president has downplayed a surge in calls to emergency hotlines, declaring most of them are false.
Victims themselves may be afraid to call for help if they live with the aggressor, or even to file claims. "If authorities arrive. If they arrive which we all know that they sometimes don‚Äôt due to the Low resources in government agencies available to the people.

This needs to change and I feel like we have the opportunity to help when we go to Mexico on vacation every year for the towns festivals by creating awareness which in Mexico is very rare since there are still a lot of the male machismo crap going around.
#femicidio #femicide #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #protectourfemales

img__alt: Photo by Kamila Kunda on December 07, 2022.
initial_comment:
Mexico has for years had a reputation of being a dangerous country for girls and women. In 2019 alone 1,006 women became victims of femicide; the unofficial figures are said to be much higher, especially when it comes to indigenous women and migrants from other Latin American countries.

‚ÄúPrayers for the Stolen‚Äù (‚ÄúNoche de fuego‚Äù, 2021) by Tatiana Huezo tells the story of three young girls living in a small mountainous town, terrorised by local drug cartels. Their friendship is extraordinary - they use telepathy to communicate with each other and the scenes in which they practise it were the most moving ones for me. Ana‚Äôs mother, like many others, forced to work on poppy fields in return for a promise her daughter won‚Äôt be abducted, nevertheless trains her daughter to hide when gangsters drive into the village to kidnap girls. The scene showing the girls, crying silently while sitting on hairdresser‚Äôs chairs when their beautiful long hair was cut short to make them look less attractive, was truly heartbreaking. Help from outside is almost non-existent. The police is afraid of the cartels, idealistic teachers leave the village one after another after short stints.

The film brilliantly depicts how helpless the whole community can be and how hope can be dying slowly. No matter how resilient and brave people are, it is impossible to constantly live in fear and thrive, as individuals, as families and as a community. It is deplorable that the Mexican government does not do enough to protect girls and women and that the American government does not support them adequately when they escape to the US. But Huezo avoids a political message. By focusing on a few girls and women and a typical, small community, her film is a tender, touching lesson in empathy and compassion.

initial_comment: For this week‚Äôs feminist friday we‚Äôll be looking at the ongoing scourge of femicide that is occurring within Mexico. Many women in Mexico are calling for action against Mexico‚Äôs corrupt justice system. The system has failed thousands of women who were killed and 98% of cases go unprosecuted. Cases are rising and many women feel unsafe and fear for their lives. There needs to be change and policies that help protect women, this is not just a feminist issue but a human rights issue as everyone has the right to not live in fear of being killed/murdered. #mejorvivasquecatrinas #femicide #nojusticia #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #thethreedeathsofmariselaescobedo

La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

img__alt: Photo by Nicka Morady in Feminist.
initial_comment: #challengeaccepted Thank you @bruna.sizzi @saharaness _ @__hastifazli__ for inviting me to this challenge. At first I was hesitant to post a picture but I realize that there may hav been some misunderstandings regarding why women are posting pictures of themselves using this hashtag. The intention of this challenge is to raise awareness on the subject of hate and violence against women and more specifically #femicide in Turkey, Iran and the many other countries which some women are unfortunately born into or married in close minded and sexist families. In these cases, women are often perceived as an object and ‚Äúproperty‚Äù of the man(men) of the family. Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. Stay #strong I now challenge @bitamajidi_ #istanbulturkey #iran #femicideawareness #femicideinturkey #femicideinmexico #femicideiniran #strongwomen #womenempowerment #feminismmemes

img__alt: Photo by Kamila Kunda on December 07, 2022.
initial_comment:
Mexico has for years had a reputation of being a dangerous country for girls and women. In 2019 alone 1,006 women became victims of femicide; the unofficial figures are said to be much higher, especially when it comes to indigenous women and migrants from other Latin American countries.

‚ÄúPrayers for the Stolen‚Äù (‚ÄúNoche de fuego‚Äù, 2021) by Tatiana Huezo tells the story of three young girls living in a small mountainous town, terrorised by local drug cartels. Their friendship is extraordinary - they use telepathy to communicate with each other and the scenes in which they practise it were the most moving ones for me. Ana‚Äôs mother, like many others, forced to work on poppy fields in return for a promise her daughter won‚Äôt be abducted, nevertheless trains her daughter to hide when gangsters drive into the village to kidnap girls. The scene showing the girls, crying silently while sitting on hairdresser‚Äôs chairs when their beautiful long hair was cut short to make them look less attractive, was truly heartbreaking. Help from outside is almost non-existent. The police is afraid of the cartels, idealistic teachers leave the village one after another after short stints.

The film brilliantly depicts how helpless the whole community can be and how hope can be dying slowly. No matter how resilient and brave people are, it is impossible to constantly live in fear and thrive, as individuals, as families and as a community. It is deplorable that the Mexican government does not do enough to protect girls and women and that the American government does not support them adequately when they escape to the US. But Huezo avoids a political message. By focusing on a few girls and women and a typical, small community, her film is a tender, touching lesson in empathy and compassion.

img__alt: Photo by PULP Magazine on February 13, 2020.
initial_comment:
25-year-old Ingrid Escamilla from Mexico City, Mexico was savagely murdered and skinned this past weekend.
Police officers arrived at the scene Sunday, to find Escamilla on the floor, lifeless with her body skinned and missing some organs. A 46-year-old man was also at the scene, covered in blood. Photos and videos have surfaced in which the man has admitted to stabbing the woman after a heated argument in which she threatened to kill him.
Further outrage sparked when digital news sites and local tabloids began posting extremely gruesome leaked photographs of the victim's body. One of the papers, Pasala, showed the photos on its front page alongside the headline "It was Cupid's fault." Prosecutors said they will demand the maximum sentence against the alleged perpetrator, whom police said was the woman's husband.
Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before.

initial_comment:
Some of you may have heard and some of you may not have a clue about what happened to this woman.
.
.
This 25 years old woman was murdered. She was skinned to "hide the evidence." Graphic pictures of her were leaked and posted online. One news paper went as far as to plaster it on their front page with the caption, "it was Cupid's fault." She was murdered by her husband after a heated argument. .
.
This woman was only 25 years old. Her life was cut short. She is one of the many victims of Femicide in Mexico.
.
.
For those that don't know -- "Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before." .
.
"The United Nations has rated Mexico as one of the most violent countries for women in the world."
.
.
This type of violence needs to end! What happened to Ingrid is so inhumane, especially having pictures of her mutilated body be displayed on the front page of a news paper for the world to see.
.
.
Please, if you see any graphic pictures of her do not repost them. That's just so wrong.
#IngridEscamilla #Femicide #EndFemicide #FemicideInMexico #RestInPeaceIngrid

initial_comment:
Liliana was the spontaneous decision that led to the best memories, she was the light in every room and the laughter that ricocheted across her friend group. She unknowingly documented her life through her writing, with every sentimental letter to a loved one or untamed thought scribbled onto the pages becoming a time capsule that‚Äôs kept her voice alive for decades. She was an intelligent young woman carving her own path in Mexico City, some of her greatest days at her fingertips still, but she died for her freedom.

Liliana's Invincible Summer: A Sister's Search for Justice is a powerful memoir that follows the author‚Äôs journey to seek justice for her sister, a woman murdered at the hands of her ex-boyfriend, 29 years ago. Faced with a cold case impossible to track down decades later, the author reconstructs Lilana‚Äôs story through her letters, diary entries and intimate conversations with friends and family. Like an archaeologist, the author opens and preserves her sister‚Äôs writing to build her own case archive.

What a hauntingly beautiful way to restore her sister‚Äôs legacy while drawing attention to a global issue that so many women are still faced with. It explores topics of patriarchy, femicide, toxic masculinity and systemic justice. The author goes on their own healing journey to create this personal and loving tribute to Liliana.

initial_comment:
La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

initial_comment: #challengeaccepted Thank you @bruna.sizzi @saharaness _ @__hastifazli__ for inviting me to this challenge. At first I was hesitant to post a picture but I realize that there may hav been some misunderstandings regarding why women are posting pictures of themselves using this hashtag. The intention of this challenge is to raise awareness on the subject of hate and violence against women and more specifically #femicide in Turkey, Iran and the many other countries which some women are unfortunately born into or married in close minded and sexist families. In these cases, women are often perceived as an object and ‚Äúproperty‚Äù of the man(men) of the family. Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. Stay #strong I now challenge @bitamajidi_ #istanbulturkey #iran #femicideawareness #femicideinturkey #femicideinmexico #femicideiniran #strongwomen #womenempowerment #feminismmemes

img__alt: Photo by Kamila Kunda on December 07, 2022.
initial_comment:
Mexico has for years had a reputation of being a dangerous country for girls and women. In 2019 alone 1,006 women became victims of femicide; the unofficial figures are said to be much higher, especially when it comes to indigenous women and migrants from other Latin American countries.

‚ÄúPrayers for the Stolen‚Äù (‚ÄúNoche de fuego‚Äù, 2021) by Tatiana Huezo tells the story of three young girls living in a small mountainous town, terrorised by local drug cartels. Their friendship is extraordinary - they use telepathy to communicate with each other and the scenes in which they practise it were the most moving ones for me. Ana‚Äôs mother, like many others, forced to work on poppy fields in return for a promise her daughter won‚Äôt be abducted, nevertheless trains her daughter to hide when gangsters drive into the village to kidnap girls. The scene showing the girls, crying silently while sitting on hairdresser‚Äôs chairs when their beautiful long hair was cut short to make them look less attractive, was truly heartbreaking. Help from outside is almost non-existent. The police is afraid of the cartels, idealistic teachers leave the village one after another after short stints.

The film brilliantly depicts how helpless the whole community can be and how hope can be dying slowly. No matter how resilient and brave people are, it is impossible to constantly live in fear and thrive, as individuals, as families and as a community. It is deplorable that the Mexican government does not do enough to protect girls and women and that the American government does not support them adequately when they escape to the US. But Huezo avoids a political message. By focusing on a few girls and women and a typical, small community, her film is a tender, touching lesson in empathy and compassion.

img__alt: Photo by PULP Magazine on February 13, 2020.
initial_comment:
25-year-old Ingrid Escamilla from Mexico City, Mexico was savagely murdered and skinned this past weekend.
Police officers arrived at the scene Sunday, to find Escamilla on the floor, lifeless with her body skinned and missing some organs. A 46-year-old man was also at the scene, covered in blood. Photos and videos have surfaced in which the man has admitted to stabbing the woman after a heated argument in which she threatened to kill him.
Further outrage sparked when digital news sites and local tabloids began posting extremely gruesome leaked photographs of the victim's body. One of the papers, Pasala, showed the photos on its front page alongside the headline "It was Cupid's fault." Prosecutors said they will demand the maximum sentence against the alleged perpetrator, whom police said was the woman's husband.
Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before.

initial_comment:
Some of you may have heard and some of you may not have a clue about what happened to this woman.
.
.
This 25 years old woman was murdered. She was skinned to "hide the evidence." Graphic pictures of her were leaked and posted online. One news paper went as far as to plaster it on their front page with the caption, "it was Cupid's fault." She was murdered by her husband after a heated argument. .
.
This woman was only 25 years old. Her life was cut short. She is one of the many victims of Femicide in Mexico.
.
.
For those that don't know -- "Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before." .
.
"The United Nations has rated Mexico as one of the most violent countries for women in the world."
.
.
This type of violence needs to end! What happened to Ingrid is so inhumane, especially having pictures of her mutilated body be displayed on the front page of a news paper for the world to see.
.
.
Please, if you see any graphic pictures of her do not repost them. That's just so wrong.
#IngridEscamilla #Femicide #EndFemicide #FemicideInMexico #RestInPeaceIngrid

initial_comment:
Liliana was the spontaneous decision that led to the best memories, she was the light in every room and the laughter that ricocheted across her friend group. She unknowingly documented her life through her writing, with every sentimental letter to a loved one or untamed thought scribbled onto the pages becoming a time capsule that‚Äôs kept her voice alive for decades. She was an intelligent young woman carving her own path in Mexico City, some of her greatest days at her fingertips still, but she died for her freedom.

Liliana's Invincible Summer: A Sister's Search for Justice is a powerful memoir that follows the author‚Äôs journey to seek justice for her sister, a woman murdered at the hands of her ex-boyfriend, 29 years ago. Faced with a cold case impossible to track down decades later, the author reconstructs Lilana‚Äôs story through her letters, diary entries and intimate conversations with friends and family. Like an archaeologist, the author opens and preserves her sister‚Äôs writing to build her own case archive.

What a hauntingly beautiful way to restore her sister‚Äôs legacy while drawing attention to a global issue that so many women are still faced with. It explores topics of patriarchy, femicide, toxic masculinity and systemic justice. The author goes on their own healing journey to create this personal and loving tribute to Liliana.

initial_comment: For this week‚Äôs feminist friday we‚Äôll be looking at the ongoing scourge of femicide that is occurring within Mexico. Many women in Mexico are calling for action against Mexico‚Äôs corrupt justice system. The system has failed thousands of women who were killed and 98% of cases go unprosecuted. Cases are rising and many women feel unsafe and fear for their lives. There needs to be change and policies that help protect women, this is not just a feminist issue but a human rights issue as everyone has the right to not live in fear of being killed/murdered. #mejorvivasquecatrinas #femicide #nojusticia #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #thethreedeathsofmariselaescobedo

initial_comment:
La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

img__alt: Photo by Nicka Morady in Feminist.
initial_comment: #challengeaccepted Thank you @bruna.sizzi @saharaness _ @__hastifazli__ for inviting me to this challenge. At first I was hesitant to post a picture but I realize that there may hav been some misunderstandings regarding why women are posting pictures of themselves using this hashtag. The intention of this challenge is to raise awareness on the subject of hate and violence against women and more specifically #femicide in Turkey, Iran and the many other countries which some women are unfortunately born into or married in close minded and sexist families. In these cases, women are often perceived as an object and ‚Äúproperty‚Äù of the man(men) of the family. Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. Stay #strong I now challenge @bitamajidi_ #istanbulturkey #iran #femicideawareness #femicideinturkey #femicideinmexico #femicideiniran #strongwomen #womenempowerment #feminismmemes

In response to the high rate of femicide in Mexico, an estimated 80,000 women took to the streets in a mass protest yesterday. The number of femicides in Mexico has increased 137% in the last five years, according to Mexico‚Äôs Attorney General. Today, women in Mexico continued their strikes by imagining #ADayWithoutWomen ‚Äîwhere women stayed home from work, school, and social media to demonstrate against the high levels of gender-based violence and demand action. Today we join in solidarity with the women of Mexico in demanding action against femicide and applaud you all for taking a stand üëè Thank you @konplizemoreak for the initial image and @jferron0689 for capturing this year‚Äôs images andvideos. #niunamas #niunamenos #internationalwomensday #womenshistorymonth #womensmonth

In 2019, a record-breaking 3,833 women were killed ‚Äî an average of over 10 every day. Many of these are cases of ‚Äúfemicide,‚Äù when a woman is killed simply for being a woman.

img__alt: Photo by The Guardian on March 11, 2019.
initial_comment:
Human rights activists in Mexico have criticised a government plan to cut funding for women's shelters, and give the money directly to victims of domestic violence instead. They warn slashing funding to shelters risk undoing decades of work by civil society organisations and exposes women and children to increased danger. In the past violent partners, neighbours and parents have beaten women to take money from government programmes. According to the United Nations, Mexico has one of the highest femicide rates in the world. Seven women are murdered by men on average every day.
Photos: Pedro Pardo + Anadolu Agency

img__alt: Photo by Global Citizen in Mexico City, Mexico.
initial_comment: Women in 2017: Last year, more the 2,000 women were victims of femicide in Mexico last year, killed simply because of their gender. On Dis de los Muertos, women in Mexico City took to the streets, wearing traditional face paint and carrying signings to protest the rampant violence against women and to call for justice for the victims. From the Women‚Äôs March to national protests, women this year stood up, spoke out for equality, and were a force to be reckoned with. Go to the link in bio to read about more moments where women, nevertheless persisted in 2017. (üì∑: Rebecca Blackwell/AP) #womenandgirls #diadelosmuertos #mexicocity #protest #activism

Translations: ‚ÄúWe are not hysterical, we are making history.‚Äù ‚ÄúThere is no worse virus than the patriarchy.‚Äù ‚ÄúI march because I am alive and not sure for how long.‚Äù

According to an article by JusticeinMexico.org, ‚ÄúFemicide, the murder of a woman, in particular committed by a man, on account of her gender, is not new to Mexico. The majority of femicides victims are stabbed, beaten to death, or strangled. The interpersonal violence against women in Mexico has staggered over the past ten years, catching the attention of many civil society organizations, both inside and outside of Mexico. Human rights efforts are often dedicated to building public-will to address and resolve gender related crimes.‚Äù

As a woman born in Mexico, I cannot stay silent about the horrifying deaths happening to women, girls, and children in Mexico (and all around the globe to be honest). Mujeres being raped, beaten, and killed by men that they know, and no accountability is ever made. The Mexican government doesn‚Äôt do anything about these crimes which says a lot about how they feel about women. Murderers, rapists, abusers need to be held accountable for their actions or else, they will continue to do it. What‚Äôs worse is the criticisms that Mexican feminists receive for standing against injustice. They are often called ‚Äúfeminazis‚Äù or ‚Äúhysterical‚Äù for not wanting to die as if that‚Äôs such a radical idea. She has every fucking right to burn and break shit. üëäüèΩIn solidarity with feminist activists in Mexico fighting against femicide. Fuck the patriarchy. #niunamenos

Translations: ‚ÄúWe are not hysterical, we are making history.‚Äù ‚ÄúThere is no worse virus than the patriarchy.‚Äù ‚ÄúI march because I am alive and not sure for how long.‚Äù

According to an article by JusticeinMexico.org, ‚ÄúFemicide, the murder of a woman, in particular committed by a man, on account of her gender, is not new to Mexico. The majority of femicides victims are stabbed, beaten to death, or strangled. The interpersonal violence against women in Mexico has staggered over the past ten years, catching the attention of many civil society organizations, both inside and outside of Mexico. Human rights efforts are often dedicated to building public-will to address and resolve gender related crimes.‚Äù

As a woman born in Mexico, I cannot stay silent about the horrifying deaths happening to women, girls, and children in Mexico (and all around the globe to be honest). Mujeres being raped, beaten, and killed by men that they know, and no accountability is ever made. The Mexican government doesn‚Äôt do anything about these crimes which says a lot about how they feel about women. Murderers, rapists, abusers need to be held accountable for their actions or else, they will continue to do it. What‚Äôs worse is the criticisms that Mexican feminists receive for standing against injustice. They are often called ‚Äúfeminazis‚Äù or ‚Äúhysterical‚Äù for not wanting to die as if that‚Äôs such a radical idea. These girls/women/mothers/protestors are putting a lot on the line and the least we can do is listen and help their cause. Hear the last video of a mother who‚Äôs daughter was murdered. She has every fucking right to burn and break shit. üëäüèΩIn solidarity with feminist activists in Mexico fighting against femicide. Fuck the patriarchy. #niunamenos

img__alt: Photo by Almost on April 29, 2022.
initial_comment:
The disappearance and death of Debanhi Escobar, an 18-year-old law student in Mexico, has caused public outrage over gender violence in the country.

In the early hours of April 9, Escobar‚Äôs friends hired a private driver to pick her up after a house party. Escobar then got out the vehicle on the side of a highway but never returned home.

A photo of her snapped by the driver has become one of the last time she was seen alive.

The image, which has since gone viral, shows the teen with her arms crossed in the middle of a highway on the outskirts of Monterrey, Nuevo Leon.

At around 4:30am, CCTV footage showed her asking for help at a transport company. She was not seen again.

After 13 days missing, Escobar‚Äôs body was found on April 22 inside an abandoned underground water tank of a motel in Escobedo city, near where she was last seen.

Two motel workers had found her after they noticed a foul odor coming from one of the water tanks.

Officials say the cause of death was a ‚Äúprofound contusion to the skull‚Äù, Reuters reported.

Authorities have yet to determine why Escobar exited the car, but her father said the driver had tried to grope his daughter, citing video footage.

‚ÄúMy daughter is dead because of incompetent (authorities), and because of sexual harassers,‚Äù Mario Escobar told local media.

An investigation is ongoing. The driver has been interviewed twice, the New York Times reported.

Authorities‚Äô handling of the case has fueled public anger, as it took almost two weeks for Escobar‚Äôs body to be found, even though the motel was searched four times, according to El Pa√≠s.

26 women and girls have vanished in Nuevo Leon this year, and five more have been found dead after they were reported missing, according to Reuters.

After Escobar‚Äôs body was found, Mexican president Andr√©s Manuel L√≥pez Obrador was criticized for telling citizens there was no need to fear and ‚Äúthis happens everywhere.‚Äù

Protesters are demanding justice for Escobar and other missing women, as well as an end to gender violence.

10 women are killed every day in Mexico, and 25,000 women are missing nationally, official data shows. (üì∏: @debanhi.escobar, Getty, Reuters, üìù: @fuermin_h, @kassy)

img__alt: Photo by Bloomberg Originals on February 16, 2020.
initial_comment:
Women in Mexico City are protesting the brutal murder and dismemberment of a 25-year-old woman at the hands of her alleged partner.

Dozens spray-painted slogans such as ‚Äúwe won't be silenced‚Äù and ‚Äúthey are killing us‚Äù on Mexico City's National Palace.

Ingrid Escamilla was killed by her alleged boyfriend last weekend. "Today we want to say that we are not angry. We are furious. And the only reason they think we feminists are a nightmare for a Mexico that kills us is because they know they are the aggressors,‚Äù says one protestor. ‚ÄúThey do not feel safe anymore. Because they no longer have the luxury of our silence." Local media published photos of Escamilla‚Äôs skinned corpse, apparently leaked by police.

This incident serves as a tipping point in an ongoing issue pertaining to how violence against women is handled and reported on.

According to official data, 10 women are killed each day in Mexico.

img__alt: Photo shared by Somos on May 04, 2022 tagging @marianaliru.
initial_comment:
In Mexico, like many parts of Latin America, there is a femicide crisis. In 2021, about 1,015 women were murdered because of their gender. However, this number is likely higher due to the vast amount of cases that remain unreported. Much of the gender-based killings, sexual assaults, and disappearances that occur in Mexico take place along the U.S.-Mexico border, in towns much like my own: Monterrey, Nuevo Le√≥n.

Such was the case of Debhani Escobar, an 18-year-old law student who disappeared on the early hours of April 9 after being dropped off by a taxi driver on a highway near a motel. Thirteen days later, Escobar‚Äôs decomposing body was found in a subterranean water tank at the motel. Escobar's death is the latest in a string of gender-related killings and disappearances of young women this year. In fact, the week of her disappearance, local media reported that another eight young women had gone missing in Nuevo Le√≥n in 10 days.
-
Mexican writer @marianaliru pens about two of the latest victims of gendered violence in Northern Mexico, Debhani Escobar and Fernanda Contreras, and the reality of being a Mexican woman in a state that borders the U.S. Link in bio.

img__alt: Photo by The Guardian on March 11, 2019.
initial_comment:
Human rights activists in Mexico have criticised a government plan to cut funding for women's shelters, and give the money directly to victims of domestic violence instead. They warn slashing funding to shelters risk undoing decades of work by civil society organisations and exposes women and children to increased danger. In the past violent partners, neighbours and parents have beaten women to take money from government programmes. According to the United Nations, Mexico has one of the highest femicide rates in the world. Seven women are murdered by men on average every day.
Photos: Pedro Pardo + Anadolu Agency

initial_comment:
Translations: ‚ÄúWe are not hysterical, we are making history.‚Äù ‚ÄúThere is no worse virus than the patriarchy.‚Äù ‚ÄúI march because I am alive and not sure for how long.‚Äù

According to an article by JusticeinMexico.org, ‚ÄúFemicide, the murder of a woman, in particular committed by a man, on account of her gender, is not new to Mexico. The majority of femicides victims are stabbed, beaten to death, or strangled. The interpersonal violence against women in Mexico has staggered over the past ten years, catching the attention of many civil society organizations, both inside and outside of Mexico. Human rights efforts are often dedicated to building public-will to address and resolve gender related crimes.‚Äù

Mujeres being raped, beaten, and killed by men that they know, and no accountability is ever made. Femicide in Mexico is skyrocketing with nearly 10 women murdered every day. Meanwhile, Mexican President Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador has denied the reality of the violence and dismissed the all-time-high phone calls to domestic violence hotlines by saying, ‚ÄúNinety per cent of those calls that you‚Äôre referring to are fake."

Obrador's administration has also publicly claimed their allegiance to support "transgender & LGBT rights". We know that "transgender rights" & "LGBT rights" are being used as dog whistle for the forced inclusion of males into sex segregated spaces for women & children and the erasure of females in both language and law.

In the United States women's domestic violence shelters have been undergoing severe attacks including defunding for what is becoming an increasingly vilified act, attempting to protect vulnerable women and create male free spaces for them during their greatest times of need.

Changes to the Violence Against Women Act have forced women's domestic violence and rape crisis centers to house men who claim to "identify as women". This has resulted in many cases where females have been verbally, physically, and sexually harassed and assaulted by males who "identify as women" --including a case in California where 9 women are suing for being forced to shower with a transgender identified male who sexually harassed them. Visit my website for EXCLUSIVE access to a two part video about the changes being made to the Violence Against Women act. The videos were banned from Youtube under the allegation of Hate Speech.

Can you see the problem?? Transgender ideology erases the reality of sex based violence against women and girls and "transgender rights" propaganda is being used to manipulate the males in to believing women who oppose the erasure of the sex based rights of women and girls are evil and bigoted. Truly diabolical.

La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

img__alt: Photo by Gender & Sexuality Equity Coalition on October 30, 2020.
initial_comment: For this week‚Äôs feminist friday we‚Äôll be looking at the ongoing scourge of femicide that is occurring within Mexico. Many women in Mexico are calling for action against Mexico‚Äôs corrupt justice system. The system has failed thousands of women who were killed and 98% of cases go unprosecuted. Cases are rising and many women feel unsafe and fear for their lives. There needs to be change and policies that help protect women, this is not just a feminist issue but a human rights issue as everyone has the right to not live in fear of being killed/murdered. #mejorvivasquecatrinas #femicide #nojusticia #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #thethreedeathsofmariselaescobedo

img__alt: Photo by Alma Lopez Digital Diva on March 07, 2021.
initial_comment:
La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

img__alt: Photo by Kamila Kunda on December 07, 2022.
initial_comment:
Mexico has for years had a reputation of being a dangerous country for girls and women. In 2019 alone 1,006 women became victims of femicide; the unofficial figures are said to be much higher, especially when it comes to indigenous women and migrants from other Latin American countries.

‚ÄúPrayers for the Stolen‚Äù (‚ÄúNoche de fuego‚Äù, 2021) by Tatiana Huezo tells the story of three young girls living in a small mountainous town, terrorised by local drug cartels. Their friendship is extraordinary - they use telepathy to communicate with each other and the scenes in which they practise it were the most moving ones for me. Ana‚Äôs mother, like many others, forced to work on poppy fields in return for a promise her daughter won‚Äôt be abducted, nevertheless trains her daughter to hide when gangsters drive into the village to kidnap girls. The scene showing the girls, crying silently while sitting on hairdresser‚Äôs chairs when their beautiful long hair was cut short to make them look less attractive, was truly heartbreaking. Help from outside is almost non-existent. The police is afraid of the cartels, idealistic teachers leave the village one after another after short stints.

The film brilliantly depicts how helpless the whole community can be and how hope can be dying slowly. No matter how resilient and brave people are, it is impossible to constantly live in fear and thrive, as individuals, as families and as a community. It is deplorable that the Mexican government does not do enough to protect girls and women and that the American government does not support them adequately when they escape to the US. But Huezo avoids a political message. By focusing on a few girls and women and a typical, small community, her film is a tender, touching lesson in empathy and compassion.

img__alt: Photo by Nicka Morady in Feminist.
initial_comment: #challengeaccepted Thank you @bruna.sizzi @saharaness _ @__hastifazli__ for inviting me to this challenge. At first I was hesitant to post a picture but I realize that there may hav been some misunderstandings regarding why women are posting pictures of themselves using this hashtag. The intention of this challenge is to raise awareness on the subject of hate and violence against women and more specifically #femicide in Turkey, Iran and the many other countries which some women are unfortunately born into or married in close minded and sexist families. In these cases, women are often perceived as an object and ‚Äúproperty‚Äù of the man(men) of the family. Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. Stay #strong I now challenge @bitamajidi_ #istanbulturkey #iran #femicideawareness #femicideinturkey #femicideinmexico #femicideiniran #strongwomen #womenempowerment #feminismmemes
For #diadelosmuertos women protested femicide in Mexico City, carrying photos of their murdered sisters, daughters and friends #FeministFriday @nowthisher

img__alt: Photo by Gender & Sexuality Equity Coalition on October 30, 2020.
initial_comment: For this week‚Äôs feminist friday we‚Äôll be looking at the ongoing scourge of femicide that is occurring within Mexico. Many women in Mexico are calling for action against Mexico‚Äôs corrupt justice system. The system has failed thousands of women who were killed and 98% of cases go unprosecuted. Cases are rising and many women feel unsafe and fear for their lives. There needs to be change and policies that help protect women, this is not just a feminist issue but a human rights issue as everyone has the right to not live in fear of being killed/murdered. #mejorvivasquecatrinas #femicide #nojusticia #femicideawareness #femicideinmexico #thethreedeathsofmariselaescobedo

img__alt: Photo by Alma Lopez Digital Diva on March 07, 2021.
initial_comment:
La Llorona Desperately Seeking Coyolxauhqui in Juarez serigraph produced at Sam Coronado Studio in Austin, Texas, 2003.

This was my first print at Coronado Studios and the first print I‚Äôve done that I felt successfully combined photography based digital with silkscreen.

This print is a study in pink focusing on the femicides on the U.S.-Mexico border which unfortunately continue today.

The second image is of the 8 foot high altar installation at TroÃÅpico de Nopal Gallery, Los Angeles.

Third image is the conference poster at UCLA organized by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Fourth image is a poster designed to bring attention to these awful torture crimes. The poster titled I was inspired by the detective novel Desert Blood by Alicia Gaspar De Alba.

Last image is the book of the conference proceedings with the cover of my La Llorona print edited by Alicia Gaspar De Alba with her then graduate student, Georgina Guzman.

img__alt: Photo by Kamila Kunda on December 07, 2022.
initial_comment:
Mexico has for years had a reputation of being a dangerous country for girls and women. In 2019 alone 1,006 women became victims of femicide; the unofficial figures are said to be much higher, especially when it comes to indigenous women and migrants from other Latin American countries.

‚ÄúPrayers for the Stolen‚Äù (‚ÄúNoche de fuego‚Äù, 2021) by Tatiana Huezo tells the story of three young girls living in a small mountainous town, terrorised by local drug cartels. Their friendship is extraordinary - they use telepathy to communicate with each other and the scenes in which they practise it were the most moving ones for me. Ana‚Äôs mother, like many others, forced to work on poppy fields in return for a promise her daughter won‚Äôt be abducted, nevertheless trains her daughter to hide when gangsters drive into the village to kidnap girls. The scene showing the girls, crying silently while sitting on hairdresser‚Äôs chairs when their beautiful long hair was cut short to make them look less attractive, was truly heartbreaking. Help from outside is almost non-existent. The police is afraid of the cartels, idealistic teachers leave the village one after another after short stints.

The film brilliantly depicts how helpless the whole community can be and how hope can be dying slowly. No matter how resilient and brave people are, it is impossible to constantly live in fear and thrive, as individuals, as families and as a community. It is deplorable that the Mexican government does not do enough to protect girls and women and that the American government does not support them adequately when they escape to the US. But Huezo avoids a political message. By focusing on a few girls and women and a typical, small community, her film is a tender, touching lesson in empathy and compassion.

Often when women find the courage to speak up and/or ask for things that are our basic human rights, it results in some kind of violence and in extreme cases the woman being murdered and then justified as ‚Äúhonor killing‚Äù. Not many in the world ( in North America specifically) know that these problems still exist in some parts of the world. This movement started by Turkish women as everyday a picture of a woman is posted in the newspaper after being killed by a boyfriend, husband, brother, father or any other family member. Be #brave. img__alt: Photo by PULP Magazine on February 13, 2020.
initial_comment:
25-year-old Ingrid Escamilla from Mexico City, Mexico was savagely murdered and skinned this past weekend.
Police officers arrived at the scene Sunday, to find Escamilla on the floor, lifeless with her body skinned and missing some organs. A 46-year-old man was also at the scene, covered in blood. Photos and videos have surfaced in which the man has admitted to stabbing the woman after a heated argument in which she threatened to kill him.
Further outrage sparked when digital news sites and local tabloids began posting extremely gruesome leaked photographs of the victim's body. One of the papers, Pasala, showed the photos on its front page alongside the headline "It was Cupid's fault." Prosecutors said they will demand the maximum sentence against the alleged perpetrator, whom police said was the woman's husband.
Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before.

initial_comment:
Some of you may have heard and some of you may not have a clue about what happened to this woman.
.
.
This 25 years old woman was murdered. She was skinned to "hide the evidence." Graphic pictures of her were leaked and posted online. One news paper went as far as to plaster it on their front page with the caption, "it was Cupid's fault." She was murdered by her husband after a heated argument. .
.
This woman was only 25 years old. Her life was cut short. She is one of the many victims of Femicide in Mexico.
.
.
For those that don't know -- "Femicides -- the killing of women on account of their gender -- have risen in Mexico in recent years; 1,006 cases were reported in 2019, compared with 912 the year before." .
.
"The United Nations has rated Mexico as one of the most violent countries for women in the world."
.
.
This type of violence needs to end! What happened to Ingrid is so inhumane, especially having pictures of her mutilated body be displayed on the front page of a news paper for the world to see.
.
.
Please, if you see any graphic pictures of her do not repost them. That's just so wrong.
#IngridEscamilla #Femicide #EndFemicide #FemicideInMexico #RestInPeaceIngrid

initial_comment:
Liliana was the spontaneous decision that led to the best memories, she was the light in every room and the laughter that ricocheted across her friend group. She unknowingly documented her life through her writing, with every sentimental letter to a loved one or untamed thought scribbled onto the pages becoming a time capsule that‚Äôs kept her voice alive for decades. She was an intelligent young woman carving her own path in Mexico City, some of her greatest days at her fingertips still, but she died for her freedom.

Liliana's Invincible Summer: A Sister's Search for Justice is a powerful memoir that follows the author‚Äôs journey to seek justice for her sister, a woman murdered at the hands of her ex-boyfriend, 29 years ago. Faced with a cold case impossible to track down decades later, the author reconstructs Lilana‚Äôs story through her letters, diary entries and intimate conversations with friends and family. Like an archaeologist, the author opens and preserves her sister‚Äôs writing to build her own case archive.

What a hauntingly beautiful way to restore her sister‚Äôs legacy while drawing attention to a global issue that so many women are still faced with. It explores topics of patriarchy, femicide, toxic masculinity and systemic justice. The author goes on their own healing journey to create this personal and loving tribute to Liliana.

img__alt: Photo shared by Tiny Feminist Notes on March 12, 2021 tagging @onumujeresmx, @collages_feminicides_mexico, and @femicides_in_mexico_.
initial_comment:
Before the just celebrated International Women‚Äôs Day, the government of Mexico erected a fence to protect Mexico's National Palace due to planned marches to mark the Day.
This was in turn turned into a memorial by women's rights activists who wrote the words, "Victims of Femicide" in huge letters and the names of thousands of victims on this 3m high barrier.
It was a way to draw attention to the hundreds of femicide victims killed every year in Mexico where reports show that the government is not doing enough to combat it.
‚ö†Ô∏èFigures suggest a staggering number of at least 939 victims of femicide was recorded in 2020 alone‚ö†Ô∏è

img__alt: Photo by ICDO on March 13, 2021.
initial_comment:
üíúSix women are killed every hour around the world, most by men in their own family or their partners. üíú

The #femicide is mostly severe in the Middle East, India and Latin and South Americas. üÜò

Although countries have enacted laws to address violence against women and proper criminal procedures for the murder of women, #ICDO believes that laws are still extremely weak and implementation spotty.

Through our projects in South and Latin America, we're participating in the process of educating men and women and raising awareness of those dreadfull practices, escalated during #covid19 pandemic lockdown in 2020.

We urge for practices as femicide to be noticed, highlighted, measured, prevented at the earliest stage and properly addressed within the legal framework.

Photo credits: @jessicafdzg üíú @marce.vela

#safeguardingdiversity #niunamenos #niunamas #stopkillingwomen #femicideawareness #ICDOMexico #MayaVoice #ICDOColombia

img__alt: Photo by Global Citizen in Mexico City, Mexico.
initial_comment: Women in 2017: Last year, more the 2,000 women were victims of femicide in Mexico last year, killed simply because of their gender. On Dis de los Muertos, women in Mexico City took to the streets, wearing traditional face paint and carrying signings to protest the rampant violence against women and to call for justice for the victims. From the Women‚Äôs March to national protests, women this year stood up, spoke out for equality, and were a force to be reckoned with. Go to the link in bio to read about more moments where women, nevertheless persisted in 2017. (üì∑: Rebecca Blackwell/AP) #womenandgirls #diadelosmuertos #mexicocity #protest #activism
